icID=3340.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> My employer and credit cards</span><hr size=1> Ok, I’ve got a bit of a rant.  A little history to set the scene, in the past I have had a HEAVY dependence on credit cards and I’ve just about got it under control.   I work a second job to get the credit cards under control faster, be able to put some back for emergencies and have the extras like EQ and internet service.   Bare bones, I could probably get by without the second job, but it makes life a lot more comfortable.<br>
<br>
Yesterday at my part time job (cashiering), they hand out a form that we have to sign stating that we will ask each and every customer that comes through our line to apply for the stores Visa card.  Failure to comply will result in reprimand on the first offense and eventually dismissal from the company.  They have even gone so far as to set a quota of credit applications that you should turn in.  Having first hand knowledge of how destructive credit cards can be and knowing that the majority of people do NOT handle credit responsibly, I have a serious problem trying to force credit cards on my customers.  So, do I sign it and give up my integrity or refuse, resign and keep my integrity in tact?  Am I wrong for feeling like the company is only after the all mighty dollar and doesn’t give a damn about their customers?  Am I making too big an issue of this?<br>
<br>
BTW, anyone want to apply for a Visa card? (j/k) <br>
